Differential Expression Analysis for GSE37382

ALSF CCDL - Candace Savonen

Purpose: This notebook tests differential expression in probe data from author-submitted version of GSE37382, a medulloblastoma microarray dataset.

The results from this differential expression analysis is used in the following notebook to compare how the processing of this microarray data affects differential expression outcomes. The data here are medulloblastoma microarray data produced by Northcott et al, 2012 and are obtained from Gene Expression Omnibus (GEO).

1) Install libraries

This script uses the bioconductor R package limma to identify differentially expressed genes.
The full guide on limma shows examples of limma functions.
We will also use the library GEOquery to obtain the author-processed data.

if (!("limma" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install limma
  BiocManager::install("limma", update = FALSE)
}
if (!("GEOquery" %in% installed.packages())) {
  # Install GEOquery
  BiocManager::install("GEOquery", update = FALSE)
}

Attach the limma library:

# Magrittr pipe
`%>%` <- dplyr::`%>%`

# Attach library

# Define the file path to the results directory

3) Extract metadata for this dataset

# Extract metadata
metadata <- data.frame(geo.data[[1]]@phenoData@data) %>% 
  # Get rid of columns that have only NAs
  dplyr::select(-which(apply(is.na(.), 2, all))) 

# Double check if metadata and data are in same order
all.equal(metadata$geo_accession, colnames(author.df))
[1] TRUE
# Print out metadata so we can get an idea of what we have
metadata

4) Set up design matrix

limma needs a numeric design matrix to signify which are treatment and control samples.

# Set up group names 
subgroup <- as.factor(gsub("Group 3|Group 4", "NonSHH", metadata$subgroup.ch1))

# Create the design matrix
des.mat <- model.matrix(~ subgroup)

# Make the column name more informative
colnames(des.mat)[2] <- paste0(levels(subgroup), collapse = "vs")

5) Apply linear model

After applying our data to linear model, in this example we apply empirical Bayes smoothing and Benjamini-Hochberg multiple testing correction.

# Initial fit
fit <- lmFit(author.df, design = des.mat)

# Make contrasts
fit <- eBayes(fit)

Obtain summary statistics:

# Apply multiple testing correction and obtain stats
stats <- topTable(fit, number = nrow(author.df)) %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("affy_probe_ids")
Removing intercept from test coefficients
# Print out stats
stats

6) Double check results directions with a boxplot

Let’s pick a probe from the results to double check our output.

stats[32, ]

According to the data above, we should see that affy probe id 8154846 should be higher in SHH group data than in NonSHH group data. Let’s extract this data and make a bopxplot to check if that is what we see.

# Extract a gene's data from the original refine.bio data.frame
test.probe <- author.df %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("probe_ids") %>%
  dplyr::filter(probe_ids == stats$affy_probe_ids[32]) %>%
  dplyr::select(-probe_ids) %>%
  t()

# Make a dataframe with the group information
box.plot <- data.frame(test.probe, subgroup) %>%
# Use ggplot2 to make a boxplot from this info
ggplot2::ggplot(., ggplot2::aes(x = subgroup, y = test.probe)) + 
  ggplot2::geom_boxplot() + 
  ggplot2::theme_classic() +
  ggplot2::ggtitle(paste("Probe ID:", stats$affy_probe_ids[32]))

# Print the plot here
box.plot

Looks like what we would expect to see.

7) Write statistics to output results file

# Save summary statistics to a tsv file
readr::write_tsv(stats, file.path(results_dir, "GSE37382_limma_results.tsv"))
